schema.headline: Live updates: Sydney FC face Western United in the 2022-23 A-League Women grand final

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Thoughts? Feelings? Vibes?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: I'm exhausted having just watched that half of football. The extended stoppage-time reflects how crash-and-bash it's been, with several players hobbling off while gripping at various parts of their bruised bodies. As expected, Sydney FC have dominated possession, territory, passes, corners, and shots on target, though Western haven't been totally out of it - particularly not in transition through the excellent and hungry Hannah Keane. 45 minutes to go. How does this one end, friends? Does Sydney add to their tally, or simply hold on? Can Western claw one back? Who will stand up and be the hero for their side?

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 45 minutes are up
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: We're at the discretion of the referee now. Sydney FC keep coming, with Haley being spoken to after contesting an aerial duel with Western goalkeeper Beall, who comes off second-best against the American. There are some tired bodies out there already. Who should Ante Juric and Mark Torcaso turn to on their bench? Who could change the game for Western? Or who could seal it for Sydney?

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 42' Sydney coming in waves
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The Sky Blues have faded somewhat in the back-end of this half, allowing Western a couple opportunities to slice through them and take a good look at goal. Cortnee Vine looks cooked - the ankle-roll she suffered earlier isn't allowing her to move freely anymore - so it seems like most of Sydney's attacks will need to be coming down the opposite wing. Princess Ibini, Sarah Hunter, and Mackenzie Hawkesby have all found themselves in dangerous positions, but Western's defenders have rallied quickly each time to prevent clear shots on target. There's gonna have to be a change for Vine at half-time, which could throw Sydney's system slightly out of whack and could give Western another crack to exploit.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 39' Whyman to the rescue!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: A nice series of passes by Western down the right wing sees the ball cut back towards the penalty spot. Sydney scuff their clearance, with the ball falling perfectly into the stride of a Western player, who arcs her leg backwards to unleash a shot. Whyman comes FLYING off her line and makes her body big as Sydney's defenders throw themselves in front of the ball, with the eventual shot coming off the goalkeeper's strong right hand and spinning away. A big few minutes for the shot-stopper!

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 37' Beware Hannah Keane
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The master goal-poacher reminds Sydney's centre-backs to always stay on their toes, pouncing on seemingly-nothing pass before turning balletically and curling it low and hard towards the bottom right corner. But Jada Whyman pulls out her best save of the game, diving low to slap it away with her left hand.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 35' Western come close!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The resulting free kick is floated into the pack by Vlajnic, and for the first time Sydney struggle to hoof it clear. The ball pings around a little bit, with Hannah Keane trying to wrestle it through the forest of legs, but it deflects out to Cummings, who puts her foot through the ball. It flies straight at Jada Mathyssen-Whyman in goal, who bobbles it before it's cleared. Big of a gasp-inducing moment for the Sydney-strong crowd.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 34' Yellow card Sydney
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Sky Blues full-back Charlie Rule gets the second yellow of the game after a kung-fu high boot on Danielle Steer's face. If these players make it out of CommBank Stadium alive, it'll be a minor miracle.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 27' Head clash
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Another corner from Sydney FC is zipped in by Hawkesby, with Charlie Rule and Sydney Cummings cracking their heads into each other as they try to contest it in the air. Both players immediately fall to the turf clutching their heads and the referee blows play dead as the two physio teams sprint out to check on their players. A few minutes pass as they go through concussion checks, but they both seem okay. Cortnee Vine, meanwhile, has quickly come off the field to get some extra strapping around the ankle she rolled earlier. Talk about putting your body on the line for your team, eh?

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 23' Yellow card Western
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: And it's the centre-back Sydney Cummings with the first slice of cheese of the game after charging into Haley as the Sky Blues try to counter-attack. Haley has got the best of Cummings a couple times now, so the defender is likely frustrated. The American, meanwhile, has been absolutely mountainous so far in this game.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 20' OUCH
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: This game is becoming a bit of a warzone. TJ Vlajnic was crunched into a few minutes ago, and just now Cortnee Vine was taken out by Cerne near the top of the box, with the slow-mo replay showing a frightening rolled ankle for the Matilda. She's back up and moving but I will admit I had a mini heart-attack when she tumbled into the grass gripping at her lower leg. In the context of the Matildas, we are very much in the Injury Hyper Awareness Window. Any tiny knock to a player feels so much worse.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 17' GOAL SYDNEY FC
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: And it's a carbon-copy of their first goal, but just with a different goal-scorer! Mackenzie Hawkesby sends a gorgeous ball to the back post, aiming for Haley's head. Goalkeeper Hillary Beall manages to punch it away, but the deflection falls right to captain Natalie Tobin, who bonks it over everybody and into the net, despite Western's best efforts to head it off the line. 2-0!!!

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 14' Alana Cerne is down
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The Western United defender falls awkwardly after getting tangled with Sydney striker Madison Haley. The replay shows her smacking into the ground hard on her side and clutching at her shoulder. Play continues for a few moments before the referee pauses the game and the physio rushes on to see if she's okay. She walks off the field gingerly a minute later before coming back on. Keep an eye on that one.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 11' Hannah Keane with a chance
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The striker plucks a long ball beautifully out of the air on her left foot and turns Sydney centre-back Charlotte McLean before stepping into the box and letting off a rocket that goes just over the bar. Keane is Western's biggest weapon, and as we saw in their semi-final win, she will take any half-chance she gets.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 8' Hello Kahli Johnson
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The young winger finds herself near the top of the box as Western launch a counter-attack. She receives a nice square ball from Danielle Steer and turns neatly away from Sarah Hunter before letting off a shot with her superb left foot that sails just over the crossbar. Western have rallied from conceding that opening goal and are starting to wrestle their way back into this one.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 7' Western chasing shadows
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: They've barely had a touch in their own attacking third in the opening few minutes. Striker Hannah Keane is having to drop very deep, almost in line with her own midfielders at times, to try and collect the ball and take it forward. Sydney FC have been dominating possession, moving the ball really well in neat triangles, as they tend to do.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: 3' GOAL SYDNEY FC
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: And the Sky Blues get their grand final off to the best possible start! A floating corner from Mackenzie Hawkesby falls right onto the head of American striker Madison Haley, who slams it down below the diving Hillary Beall and into the net. 1-0!

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Cortnee Vine goes WHACK
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Less than a minute into the game and Matildas winger Cortnee Vine gets on the ball, cutting in-field before smacking right into Western centre-back Sydney Cummings. The entire media box just went "oooooh" in vicarious pain. She looks to be a little dazed, but is up and moving now.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Predictions?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The teams have lined up, the Welcome to Country has been delivered, the anthem has been sung, and the coin has been tossed. Who takes out this one, friends? Does Sydney break their Grand Final curse? Or does Western United cap off their fairytale first season? Log in and give me your score predictions!

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Deb loves the Dub
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: couldnt careless about whether its in NSW or anywhere its a celebration of womens football in this country and for you to detract from that is absurd hopefully a great crowd great game and a spectacle our sport can be proud of anything else  is noise. After all its the biggest female sport on the planet - deb. You're right, Deb - if this new initiative is able to attract more fans and viewers to the A-League Women, and to women's football more generally, then it would arguably validate the decision by the APL to move the women's grand final to Sydney. One end of CommBank is already filling up with fans who look and sound awesome. I personally think it's a different dynamic when it comes to the A-League Men, but that's a conversation for another time.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Squads!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: If it ain't broke, don't fix it. Sydney FC come into the decider with the same starting XI as they had in their preliminary final against Melbourne Victory last week, with Nat Tobin ticking over into her 100th game. Western United, meanwhile, have made two changes from their major semi-final win over the Sky Blues two weeks ago. Full-back Angie Beard, who twisted her ankle in the turf during that game, hasn't recovered in time to feature today at all. Mel Taranto has also been replaced by Danielle Steer. Chloe Logarzo seemingly hasn't got over the niggling foot injury that kept her out of the back-half of Western's regular season, which is a bit of a shame given her game-changing abilities. Who do you reckon comes out on top of this one, team? Will Western do another smash-and-grab over the Premiers? Or will Sydney FC be too good this time? Log in and let me know!

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Hello hello!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Salut Sydney FC Sam! 🙂 - Natty. Welcome back to the blog, Natty! What's your tip for today's game?

liveBlogUpdate.headline: A fairytale finish for Western?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: It's been quite the start to life in the A-League Women for Western United. As the newest expansion franchise, there were zero expectations that the club would be able to achieve anything as they found their feet with a squad made up largely of National Premier League players (with a couple superstars like World Cup winner Jess McDonald and Matilda Chloe Logarzo thrown in), many of whom had never played top-flight football before. Boy, did they prove us wrong. They started their inaugural season with a bang, defeating reigning Champions Melbourne Victory before going on a barn-storming run to lead the league for most of the season, in part thanks to Golden Boot winner Hannah Keane. They wobbled a little bit about half-way through, but managed to cling onto their spot in the top two and even knock Sydney out of the major semi-final a few weekends ago. It's a remarkable achievement for head coach Mark Torcaso and his new side, who could be the first expansion club since Melbourne City in 2015 to win the Championship. I wrote this feature about them a while back, which talks about how the club's connection with the NPLW - providing a clear, accessible pathway from the grassroots to the professional level - is how all future expansion sides should go about their business. What have you made of their season, folks? And who do you reckon will be key for them today?

liveBlogUpdate.headline: A special game for a special player
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: Today's match is a particularly special occasion for Sydney FC captain, Natalie Tobin. In a delightful full-circle moment, Tobin made her debut for the Sky Blues all the way back in the 2012-13 grand final, which the team went on to win 3-1 against Melbourne Victory. Since then, Tobin has been a mainstay in the club, watching it transform from a team overflowing with senior Matildas to one developing the next generation of them. Poetically, this afternoon marks her 100th appearance in the ALW. And while she hasn't gone on to hit the heights of some of her former team-mates, she represents the group of women who have played a huge role in getting the league - and the wider game - to where it is today. I had a chat with Nat at the grand final launch on Friday where we talked about just how far the ALW has come in the ten years she's been involved. She tells an excellent story about peeing behind a fence. You can read it below as we wait for kick-off:

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Wait, you're *where*?
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: The not-so-subtle elephant in the room here is that I'm currently blogging to you from CommBank Stadium in Parramatta, despite the fact that neither of these grand final teams are from the area. For those who aren't aware (or, like me, have buried the information deep down in your psyches to avoid a total footballing existential crisis), this is the first iteration of the A-Leagues' decision to sell the grand final hosting rights to Destination NSW for the next three seasons. This means that Western United - although they won their major semi-final - have had to travel to Sydney for the game they would otherwise have hosted in previous years. Western midfielder Emma Robers wasn't super stoked with the decision, telling media earlier this week: "Especially being the new club, it would have been unbelievable to have a home grand final as a new team that's come into the competition and have all our family and friends there, continue to build this fan base that we're trying so hard to build. "So, I think that is a big element of that, it's disappointing that it's not at home. "I understand the financial side of it and the decision that went into that. But it's hard." Of all the issues that both the men's and women's A-Leagues have experienced this season, the grand final one has undoubtedly been the most controversial. Rusted-on fans of every club - including those in NSW - organised protests and boycotts across the ALM earlier in the season, though unfortunately their messaging got a little lost in a bucket of sand. From the APL's perspective, they want to make the grand finals a showpiece event: a kind of sporting tourist attraction aimed at casual or neutral football fans, with lots of activities and activations supposedly built around the games themselves, which they want to take place across a single weekend once the season calendars align. From the fans' perspective, the decision is a short-sighted cash-grab from a financially desperate competition, whose leaders are willing to throw out decades of tradition (i.e. the team that finishes highest gets to host the final) for a flash-in-the-pan appeal to people who don't really care about the leagues at all. Today's game will be the first test of the APL's decision: they're aiming to break the all-time ALW grand final attendance record, and have supposedly "distributed" in excess of 8,500 tickets already (whether they were sold or given away is unknown). Could it be a proof of concept if they happen to break the record? Would it be a different case if none of the teams in this grand final were actually from NSW? What do you think of the whole debacle? Log in and give me your hot takes.

liveBlogUpdate.headline: Howdy!
liveBlogUpdate.articleBody: G'day and welcome to ABC Sport's live coverage of the 2022-23 A-League Women grand final. My name is Sam Lewis and I'll be your host as five-time Premiers Sydney FC take on competition newbies Western United in the last game of the Dub's 15th (!!!) season. Narratives abound both on and off the pitch for these two sides (one of which is the location of this particular pitch itself, but more on that in a minute) as the ALW enters into its next era, bringing in more money, more teams, more players, more games, and more visibility in the wake of July's Women's World Cup. So as the teams warm up and fans begin to fill the stands, let's take a look at some of the bigger talking-points in today's match, across the season, and beyond.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's been quite the start to life in the A-League Women for Western United. As the newest expansion franchise, there were zero expectations that the club would be able to achieve anything as they found their feet with a squad made up largely of National Premier League players (with a couple superstars like World Cup winner Jess McDonald and Matilda Chloe Logarzo thrown in), many of whom had never played top-flight football before. Boy, did they prove us wrong. They started their inaugural season with a bang, defeating reigning Champions Melbourne Victory before going on a barn-storming run to lead the league for most of the season, in part thanks to Golden Boot winner Hannah Keane. They wobbled a little bit about half-way through, but managed to cling onto their spot in the top two and even knock Sydney out of the major semi-final a few weekends ago. It's a remarkable achievement for head coach Mark Torcaso and his new side, who could be the first expansion club since Melbourne City in 2015 to win the Championship. I wrote this feature about them a while back, which talks about how the club's connection with the NPLW - providing a clear, accessible pathway from the grassroots to the professional level - is how all future expansion sides should go about their business. What have you made of their season, folks? And who do you reckon will be key for them today?
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: A fairytale finish for Western?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Today's match is a particularly special occasion for Sydney FC captain, Natalie Tobin. In a delightful full-circle moment, Tobin made her debut for the Sky Blues all the way back in the 2012-13 grand final, which the team went on to win 3-1 against Melbourne Victory. Since then, Tobin has been a mainstay in the club, watching it transform from a team overflowing with senior Matildas to one developing the next generation of them. Poetically, this afternoon marks her 100th appearance in the ALW. And while she hasn't gone on to hit the heights of some of her former team-mates, she represents the group of women who have played a huge role in getting the league - and the wider game - to where it is today. I had a chat with Nat at the grand final launch on Friday where we talked about just how far the ALW has come in the ten years she's been involved. She tells an excellent story about peeing behind a fence. You can read it below as we wait for kick-off:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The not-so-subtle elephant in the room here is that I'm currently blogging to you from CommBank Stadium in Parramatta, despite the fact that neither of these grand final teams are from the area. For those who aren't aware (or, like me, have buried the information deep down in your psyches to avoid a total footballing existential crisis), this is the first iteration of the A-Leagues' decision to sell the grand final hosting rights to Destination NSW for the next three seasons. This means that Western United - although they won their major semi-final - have had to travel to Sydney for the game they would otherwise have hosted in previous years. Western midfielder Emma Robers wasn't super stoked with the decision, telling media earlier this week: "Especially being the new club, it would have been unbelievable to have a home grand final as a new team that's come into the competition and have all our family and friends there, continue to build this fan base that we're trying so hard to build. "So, I think that is a big element of that, it's disappointing that it's not at home. "I understand the financial side of it and the decision that went into that. But it's hard." Of all the issues that both the men's and women's A-Leagues have experienced this season, the grand final one has undoubtedly been the most controversial. Rusted-on fans of every club - including those in NSW - organised protests and boycotts across the ALM earlier in the season, though unfortunately their messaging got a little lost in a bucket of sand. From the APL's perspective, they want to make the grand finals a showpiece event: a kind of sporting tourist attraction aimed at casual or neutral football fans, with lots of activities and activations supposedly built around the games themselves, which they want to take place across a single weekend once the season calendars align. From the fans' perspective, the decision is a short-sighted cash-grab from a financially desperate competition, whose leaders are willing to throw out decades of tradition (i.e. the team that finishes highest gets to host the final) for a flash-in-the-pan appeal to people who don't really care about the leagues at all. Today's game will be the first test of the APL's decision: they're aiming to break the all-time ALW grand final attendance record, and have supposedly "distributed" in excess of 8,500 tickets already (whether they were sold or given away is unknown). Could it be a proof of concept if they happen to break the record? Would it be a different case if none of the teams in this grand final were actually from NSW? What do you think of the whole debacle? Log in and give me your hot takes.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wait, you're *where*?

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: G'day and welcome to ABC Sport's live coverage of the 2022-23 A-League Women grand final. My name is Sam Lewis and I'll be your host as five-time Premiers Sydney FC take on competition newbies Western United in the last game of the Dub's 15th (!!!) season. Narratives abound both on and off the pitch for these two sides (one of which is the location of this particular pitch itself, but more on that in a minute) as the ALW enters into its next era, bringing in more money, more teams, more players, more games, and more visibility in the wake of July's Women's World Cup. So as the teams warm up and fans begin to fill the stands, let's take a look at some of the bigger talking-points in today's match, across the season, and beyond.
